title: Robert (Bob) Nichols, radio announcer, ca. 1927
description: Transcribed from spl_shp_40468: "Robert Nichols. All radio listeners are familiar with the bluff, hearty voice of "Bob" Nichols, chief announcer for the American Broadcasting Company's Seattle studios. Beginning his radio career as a singer several year[s] ago, Nichols then took up announcing sports and finally was appointed chain announcer. He was born in St. Paul, Minnesota, twenty-nine years ago and is over six feet in height, weighing slightly more than two hundred pounds. He was a football, baseball and basketball star at the University of Washington and has covered all of the big Pacific Coast Conference football games for the ABC Network." Nichols is featured in the book ""Seattle Radio"" with the following description: ""Bob Nichols started as a singer on the P.I. Station KFC in 1921. By 1927, he was KJR's sports director and doing some of Seattle's first play-by-play broadcasts.""

title: David and Catherine Maynard home, ca. 1852
description: Transcribed from image: "Early Home of Mrs. D.S. [Catherine] Maynard. Built by Dr. D[avid] S. Maynard in 1852 on the corner of Commercial [later 1st Ave. S.] and Main St. and occupied by him with the first store. It was also the first place of residence of himself and wife. First election in King County was held there, and first Court of Justice of the Peace."
intersection: 1st Ave. S. and S. Main St.

title: Works Progress Administration sign at Green Lake, March 12, 1937
description: HistoryLink article "Green Lake cleanup and redesign begins in 1936" states: "In the winter of 1936, a major, WPA-funded clean-up of Seattle's Green Lake is undertaken. For decades, the lake has been subject to algae bloom and outbreaks of green scum and foul odor, and swimmers have gotten swimmer's itch. The massive project includes dredging the lake, building an island (Swan Island, or Duck Island) as a wildlife sanctuary, and building a water-aerating fountain in the middle of the lake. The fountain is never built, but other parts of the project are carried out."

Marion A. Zioncheck's suicide note, August 9, 1936
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Zioncheck's last written statement. Here is the suicide note left by Representative Marion A. Zioncheck, congressman from Seattle, before he leaped to his death from the 5th story of the Arctic Building in Seattle, August 7." The suicide note reads: "My only hope in life was to improve the condition of an unfair economic system that held no promise to those that all the wealth of even a decent chance to survive let alone live." Marion Zioncheck served as a U.S. Representative for the State of Washington between 1933 and 1936. He committed suicide in 1936 and his seat was later filled by Warren Magnuson.

title: Space Needle, 1962
Leola Trotter and her cat, June 27, 1932
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Miss Leola Trotter, of Seattle, and "King," her handsome white cat. Miss Trotter would not be unwilling to kiss the white cat, if she ever needs to lose a pound or two of weight. Convenient Method of Reducing Discovered in Dusty Pages of Ancient Records. Girls! Attention, please, while the maestro tells you something vastly interesting and - perhaps - of vaster importance. A safe, convenient, and logical method of reducing has been discovered - or rather revived and brought out from the dusty shelves of antiquity. Just as logical as - It is just as safe, convenient and logical as many of these modern schemes for eliminating excess poundage. This simple plan, dug up and out by the maestro during many long and laborious hours of burning the midnight mazdas, is known technically as the "proper" curvature of the figure thru influence of superstition. And this, translated into ordinary talk, merely means practicing or following out an old rule of superstition. In Ye Olden Days, when authorities on superstition were running high in the affairs of ordinary mortals, one of these savants evolved, declared and published this rule: "Kiss a white cat; 'twill make you lean." There you are, girls! If you don't believe it, just try it. And what, permit the maestro to ask, could be more convenient than kissing a white cat in order to do away with an extra pound or two of weight, so distressing when face to face with the scales? Reverse the Rule. Also, this same savant announced to a surprised world: "Kiss a black cat; 'twill make you fat." There you are again! If you happen to be a bit too thin, the jolly old rule is reversed as to the color of the cat - and the results are supposed to be equally satisfactory. The maestro charges nothing for this information. His interest is purely scientific."

Victor A. Meyers and his family, February 24, 1938
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Acme Newspictures. San Francisco Bureau. SF 16. Hoping to be Seattle's first family. A recent Seattle, Wash. primary election put the Victor A. Meyers family one step closer to the honor of being Seattle's first family. Meyers, Lieutenant Governor of the state and one-time band leader, was nominated to oppose Arthur B. Langlie in the March 8 election. He was backed by the C.I.O. and "Left Wing" groups. With "Vic" as he is known throughout the Pacific Northwest are his wife, daughter, Mary Louise, and son, Victor, Jr. (LA SF CL) 2-24-38." Victor's wife is listed as Goldie in the 1930 Census.

title: Marion A. Zioncheck boarding train from Chicago to Seattle, June 30, 1936
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Zioncheck leaves Chicago for home. Representative Marion Zioncheck of Washington, is shown above as he boarded a train at Chicago, June 30, enroute to his home in the west, after an evening spent in trying to evade newspapermen, during which he was taken across the municipal airport in a passenger plane, to give the impression that he would continue the trip west by air." Marion Zioncheck served as a U.S. Representative for the State of Washington between 1933 and 1936. He committed suicide in 1936 and his seat was later filled by Warren Magnuson.

title: Jackie LeMay, May 28, 1932
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Jackie Le May, propagandist for smiles. "Life," said Mr. Jackie Le May, "really is amusing. The chap who said, 'Life is a funny proposition after all,' had the right idea, whatever lugubrious viewpoint of existence may have been buzzing around in his head. As I look back over my lifetime of four years, I can see many events that had all the qualities of real humor. I laughed at them then at times I break out laughing about them even at this late date. I enjoy laughing. Frequently I feel like laughing. And so I laugh. Laughing is a tonic during and after routine of one's profession. It is good for a person, and I simply cannot figure out why more fold do not cultivate the habit. My work brings me before the public a great deal. I'm master of ceremonies for an orchestra and also I play violin at public entertainments. The newer generation of masters of ceremonies are going in strong for more laughs. Now I know it really is not polite to laugh at our public, but sometimes I just cannot help it. So many of the public are so intensely concentrated on something or other. They look glum and often they weep. They even weep at weddings. That doesn't seem at all logical. I prefer to laugh at weddings. The bridegrooms look so funny. And the brides are so very sweet." (Editor's note: Mr. Le May is a member of Seattle's Baby Orchestra, which is composed of 10 children ranging in age from 2 1/2 to 9 years.)" The same photo (with a different caption) appeared in the Seattle Times on November 25, 1932.

Marion A. Zioncheck with Texans Jack and Ed Clark, August 5, 1936
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Zioncheck's Last Picture. This photograph, the last taken of congressman Marion A. Zioncheck, was "snapped" August 5, when he met Ed Clark, (left), San Benito, Tex, high school student, and his brother, Jack Clark, a student at Texas College of Agriculture and Mechanics. The youths came to Seattle on a tour advertising the Texas Centennial Exposition, and Congressman Zioncheck, forty-eight hours before his leap to death, gave them a letter to Gov. James V. Allred." Marion Zioncheck served as a U.S. Representative for the State of Washington between 1933 and 1936. He committed suicide in 1936 and his seat was later filled by Warren Magnuson.

title: Marion A. Zioncheck being transported from Gallinger Hospital, June 23, 1936
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Rep. Zioncheck Moved. Rep. Marion Zioncheck, of Washington, angrily shouted that he was being mistreated, was carried out of Gallinger Hospital, in Washington, D.C., June 23, and hustled away in an ambulance to a private sanitarium in Baltimore. Zioncheck said the hospital authorities had him in a straightjacket, but this charge was denied by the hospital superintendent who said he was put in a "pack" because he resisted attendants when they were moving him. The "pac" - tight wrapping in sheets - has the same effect as a straightjacket. Photo shows - Rep. Zioncheck being removed from Gallinger Hospital." Marion Zioncheck served as a U.S. Representative for the State of Washington between 1933 and 1936. He committed suicide in 1936 and his seat was later filled by Warren Magnuson.

title: Space Needle from south gate of the World's Fair, 1962
description: South Entrance and Space Needle, Century 21 Exposition (Seattle World's Fair). On the South Entrance, designed by Bassetti & Morse: "Douglas fir logs turned on giant lathe by Cascade Pole Co. and painted rainbow of colors, greet visitors on south side."" (An Architect's Guidebook to the Seattle Worlds Fair. Seattle, Pacific Builder and Engineer, April 1962, p. 31). Space Needle: ""The Space Needle, a modernistic totem of the Seattle Worlds Fair, was conceived by Eddie Carlson as a doodle in 1959 and given form by architects John Graham Jr., Victor Steinbrueck, and John Ridley. When King County declined to fund the project, five private investors, Bagley Wright, Ned Skinner, Norton Clapp, John Graham Jr., and Howard S. Wright, took over and built the 605-foot tower in less than a year." (Walt Crowley, Space Needle (Seattle). HistoryLink.org, http://historylink.org/index.cfm?DisplayPage=output.cfm&file_id=1424)

Marion Zioncheck served as a U.S. Representative for the State of Washington between 1933 and 1936. He committed suicide in 1936 and his seat was later filled by Warren Magnuson.

Flag Plaza, Armory and Space Needle, 1962
description: Plaza of the States, Century 21 Exposition (Seattle Worlds Fair). "Created at the specific request of Washington's Governor Albert D. Rosellini and erected from funds voted by the Legislature, the Plaza of the States is a flag-surrounded open-air ceremonial area used for special programs honoring the fifty states. Located in the geographic center of the fairgrounds, the area contains a bandstand, speakers' platform and a huge, gas-fed flame font -- symbol of the unity of the states. The flame will burn throughout the 184 days of the Fair." (Official press book: Seattle World's Fair 1962. Seattle: Century 21 Exposition, 1962, p. 65.)
subjects: Plaza of the States (Century 21 Exposition, 1962, Seattle, Wash.)

title: Canada Pavilion and fountain, 1962
description: Canada Pavilion of the Century 21 Exposition (Seattle World's Fair). "Surrounding the Coliseum is 94,200 sq. ft. of exhibit space in clear span structures of concrete columns and tilt-up walls with a steel joist roof system and metal decking and insulation. The concrete, laid out in a repetitive form which has become the architect's trademark, relieves what might otherwise have become a monotonous perimeter facade." (An Architect's Guidebook to the Seattle World's Fair. Seattle, Pacific Builder and Engineer, April 1962, p. 19)

title: Barney Ross, national welter weight, meeting with Howard Dent Jr. from University of Washington, April 2, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1508. Barney Ross arrives in Seattle for match with Henry Wood for title. Seattle, Washington. - Barney Ross, National welter weight has arrived in Seattle to defend his title against Henry Wood, the sturdy Washingtonian in a twelve round bout in Seattle's civic auditorium next week. The champion looks good after a few weeks in the hot springs and there is little doubt that he will come out the heavy man on the tales to put Woods away in a hurry. The first man to greet Ross at the Seattle[Washington] Athletic Club Training quarters was Howard Dent, jr. heavy weight wrestler of the University of Washington. Dent is the blind wrestler who has astonished the world wi th his blind skill in the heavies. His weight is 190 pounds and he is just now slated to take on a bout at Multnomah Club of Portland in the P.N.A. of the A.A.U. wrestling tournament. Photo shows Barney Ross wishing good luck to the blind wrestler on his tour of the Northwest. Direct service...4/2/35...exclusive."

title: Bertha Barkhoff and Zoe Smith, badminton finalists, April 1, 1935
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1507. Badminton stars come through according to form. Mrs. Bert Barkhoff [Bertha] and Zoe Smith of Seattle won their place in the State finals at Badminton at Queen Anne Hall last night. After a tour of the Pacific Coast this team came right back and showed the homefolk that their awards were of the first water. They won their set be a score of 15-11 to 15-8. Photo shows Mrs. Barkhoff shooting a back-hand with Miss Zoe Smith backing up. Direct service...4/1/35...exclusive..."

title: Collapsed East Gate at World Fair grounds, February 26, 1962
description: Transcribed from photograph: "Seattle Builders' Work is Un-Fair. What goes up must come down. But workmen erecting the facilities for the Seattle World's Fair are not pleased that their work is undone before the exposition opens. A 40-foot-high laminated wooden arch at the main east entryway collapsed into a heap of splinters Monday. Construction foreman Del Yount said he thought a gust of wind did the damage. The Men were standing under the arch but escaped without injury."

title: 3rd Ave. and Jefferson St. after the fire, July 1889
Paul Satko's children being taken into custody by Juvenile Court, April 25, 1940
description: Transcribed from photograph: "562778. Children taken from Alaska-bound ark. Seattle--Despite efforts to hid in the hold of the home-made Ark of Juneau, bound from Tacoma, Wash. to Alaska, five of the minor children of Paul Satko were taken into temporary custody by the Juvenile Court at Seattle. The action came after a court order was served on Satko, ordering him to turn the children over to authorties on grounds that the ark was unsafe. Here the children are shown on their way to court. Hazel, 18, who wasn't held; Joe, 16; David, 9; Billie, 8; and Grace, 11, partly hidden. Credit line (ACME) 4-26-40." The same photograph appeared in the Seattle Times on April 25, 1940.

Miss Frazer is a University of Washington co-ed and in her recent record she got 598 out of a possible 600, which is only one point removed from an all time record, she tied last year with Mary Wettach of Carnegie Tech and lost the toss of the coin for first place. title: Hilde McAuslan, Washington State champion golfer, August 19, 1934
description: Transcribed from photograph: "SEA: 1110. Young Seattle star retains golf crown. Seattle, Washington.- Hilde McAuslan, brilliant young Seattle golfer went through the Washington State Championship contest in nearly far [sic] form to retain her hold on the state title, beating her final rival 14 up and 12 to go. Photo shows Seattle's own Hilda the perfect stylist. Direct service...8/20/34. Exclusive..." Seattle Times articles from August 19 state that the championship took place at the Broadmoor Golf Course.

title: Paul Satko's "Ark" in Tacoma, November 8, 1939
description: Transcribed from photograph: "ACME Newspictures. San Francisco Bureau. SF 17106. Weird Biblical Ark to Attempt Alaska Cruise. Tacoma, Wash.--A weird ark. Built by Paul Satko of odds and ends during the past two years, flowing on the water of Puget Sound after being launched preparatory to a proposed cruise to Alaska. Satko says the unwieldy structure will carry his family of eight to Seldovia, Alaska, where he plans to take up a homestead. Satko built the frame of the 10-ton ship in Richmond, VA. Then mounted it on a truck and drove to Tacoma. (BU) 11-8-39."
